# Delegate grunt work to zero

This machine has `zero` (terminal coding agent) configured with the `t2000`
provider — `api.t2000.ai/v1`, model `t2000/auto` (bulk → GLM 5.2 at ~10–30×
below frontier prices; auto-escalates hard steps). Burning frontier tokens on
mechanical work is the failure mode this rule exists to stop.

## When to delegate

A task qualifies when it is WELL-SPECIFIED and MECHANICAL — you could write
acceptance criteria in two sentences:

- sweeps (rename X→Y across files, update imports, fix lint warnings)
- make-the-tests-pass loops on a known suite
- boilerplate generation from an existing pattern
- doc/comment staleness sweeps with clear criteria

Do NOT delegate: ambiguous or architectural work, security-sensitive changes,
anything touching money paths (`packages/sdk` send/swap/pay logic), or tasks
where the spec IS the hard part. Those stay in the **Think** lane (Cursor) or
**Build** lane (Claude Code on Anthropic Max) — see `spend-lanes.mdc`. This
rule only covers Grind.

## How

Run in the integrated terminal, same working tree:

```bash
zero exec "<task with explicit acceptance criteria>"
zero exec --worktree "<risky/parallel task>"   # isolated git worktree
```

- Auth comes from the environment (`T2000_API_KEY`) — never put keys in the prompt.
- Noisy TTY commands (test suites, builds, watchers): tell zero to run them
  quiet — `CI=true … 2>&1 | tail -30` — raw spinner/ANSI output corrupts
  `exec` rendering (dogfood finding, 2026-07-14).
- Monitor the run; when it finishes, REVIEW THE DIFF yourself (git panel /
  `git diff`) before reporting back. You own the result, not zero.
- Never let zero commit. Commits happen through the normal review flow.
- If zero's result is wrong twice, stop delegating that task and do it yourself
  — and note the misroute (misroutes become eval cases in
  `audric/apps/web-v3/scripts/api-router-eval.ts`).
